Trade Performance Tracker

Overview

Trade Performance Tracker is a web-based tool for options traders who use Thinkorswim. It allows you to:

  • Track options positions by pasting trade confirmations directly from Thinkorswim
  • Calculate P&L automatically for open and closed positions
  • Organize trades into services/portfolios for different trading strategies
  • Mark positions to market with current values for unrealized P&L tracking
  • Track taxable vs non-taxable positions across different accounts
  • Sync to Google Sheets for backup and cross-device access

The app runs entirely in your browser - no installation required. Your data is stored locally and optionally synced to your personal Google Drive.

Ready to get started? Jump to the Getting Started section.

Application Screenshots

Main Page

The main dashboard shows the total portfolio summary at the top with aggregate statistics across all services, followed by individual service cards. Each service card displays position counts, cost, value, current P&L, and closed P&L.

Key elements: - Total Portfolio summary with position counts, cost, value, current P&L, and closed P&L - Current P&L Breakdown showing taxable vs non-taxable - Closed P&L Breakdown showing taxable vs non-taxable - Collapsible Closed P&L Chart - Service cards with individual metrics and Add Service button

Service View - Open Positions

The service detail view shows the trade entry form at the top and position cards below. The toggle switches between Open and Closed positions. Position cards show symbol, spread type, cost, value, contracts, DTE, and adjustment count.

Key elements: - Service summary statistics - Add Trade form with Thinkorswim paste input - Position number selector (existing or new) - Trade date picker - Open/Closed Positions toggle - Position cards in a responsive grid

Service View - Expanded Position

Clicking a position card expands it to show full details including trade history, mark-to-market section, and action buttons. The taxable checkbox allows marking positions for tax tracking.

Key elements: - Close/Delete buttons for position management - Taxable checkbox for tax tracking - Mark-to-Market section with current mark and set mark button - Net Position showing current leg quantities - Individual trade cards with full details (action, legs, strikes, expirations, price)

Service View - Closed Positions

The closed positions view shows positions that have been closed, with Days Held instead of DTE. Expanded positions show the full trade history including opening and closing trades.

Key elements: - Closed Positions toggle selected - Position cards showing closed status - Opened/Closed dates displayed - Days Held metric (instead of DTE) - Reopen/Delete buttons for closed positions - Full trade history in expanded view

Account Settings & Sync

The settings panel handles Google account authentication and cloud sync. Data can be synced to Google Sheets for backup and cross-device access.

Key elements: - Google Account sign in/out - Cloud Sync toggle with spreadsheet name and last sync time - Sync Now and Refresh from Cloud buttons - Direct link to open spreadsheet in Google Sheets - Export/Import for local data backup

Getting Started

Accessing the Application

The application is available at: https://options-tracker-phi.vercel.app

Simply open this URL in any modern web browser (Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge) to start using the tool.

How the Application Works

This is a client-side web application - all processing happens in your browser:


                   YOUR BROWSER                       
       
   React App      localStorage    OAuth       
   (all logic)  (JSON data)     Token       
       

                                           
         static files                       API calls
                                           
                     
      Vercel                       Google Sheets
      (host)                       (cloud data)

Key points: - Vercel is just a file server - it hosts the static HTML, JavaScript, and CSS files - Your browser downloads these files and runs the entire application locally - All calculations (P&L, positions, etc.) happen in your browser - localStorage stores your data as JSON in your browsers local database - Google Sheets (optional) provides cloud backup and cross-device sync

Data Storage & Limitations

By default, your data is stored in your browsers localStorage:

What persists: - Data survives closing and reopening the browser - Data survives computer restarts - Data persists indefinitely until cleared

Limitations - data is isolated to: - Same browser - Chrome and Safari have separate storage - Same device - your laptop and phone are separate - Same domain - tied to this specific URL

When you could lose data: - Clearing browser cache/data - Using a different browser - Using a different device - Using private/incognito mode (never persists)

Recommendation: Either enable Google Sheets sync (see below) or regularly use the Export function in Settings to create backup files.

Enabling Google Sheets Integration

Google Sheets sync provides cloud backup and allows you to access your data from any device or browser.

Step 1: Request Access

The application is currently in Googles testing mode, which limits access to pre-approved users. To get access:

Email arthomas98@gmail.com with: - Your Gmail address - A request to be added as a test user

Youll receive confirmation once added (usually within 24 hours).

Step 2: Sign In

  1. Open the application and click the Settings icon (gear) in the top right
  2. Click Sign in with Google
  3. Important: Youll see a warning screen that says This app isnt verified
    • Click Advanced
    • Click Go to Options Tracker (unsafe)
    • This warning appears because the app is in testing mode - its safe to proceed
  4. Grant the requested permissions (access to Google Sheets and Drive)

Step 3: Enable Sync

  1. After signing in, toggle Cloud Sync to enabled
  2. The app will automatically create a spreadsheet called Options Tracker Data in your Google Drive
  3. Click Sync Now to push your local data to the cloud
  4. Your data will now sync automatically when you make changes

Sync Features

  • Sync Now - Push local changes to Google Sheets
  • Refresh from Cloud - Pull data from Google Sheets to your browser
  • Open Spreadsheet - View your data directly in Google Sheets
  • Data syncs automatically when you add trades, close positions, etc.

Basic Usage

  1. Create a Service - Click + Add Service to create a portfolio (e.g., My Trades)
  2. Add Trades - Paste Thinkorswim trade strings into the Add Trade form
  3. Assign Position Numbers - Group related trades by assigning the same position number
  4. Track P&L - View real-time cost basis and P&L calculations
  5. Mark Positions - Enter current market values for unrealized P&L tracking
  6. Close Positions - Mark positions as closed when you exit trades

Original Requirements

Input: I will cut and paste in trade transactions from Thinkorswim. Here are some samples:

  • BUY +2 BE 100 15 JAN 27 50 CALL @52.60 LMT
  • SELL -7 2/2/-1/-1 CUSTOM GOOGL 100 (Weeklys) 6 FEB 26/6 FEB 26/30 JAN 26/30 JAN 26 355/295/355/295 CALL/PUT/CALL/PUT @11.99 LMT GTC
  • SELL -4 CALENDAR SHOP 100 (Weeklys) 13 FEB 26/16 JAN 26 160 PUT @6.75 LMT
  • SELL -20 VERT ROLL RUT 100 (Weeklys) 20 FEB 26/30 JAN 26 2730/2740/2730/2740 CALL @.40 LMT
  • SELL -4 CALENDAR SHOP 100 15 MAY 26/13 FEB 26 160 PUT @7.15 LMT
  • SELL -2 CL 100 20 MAR 26 85 CALL @3.55 LMT
  • BUY +10 HIMS 100 18 SEP 26 40 CALL @5.45 LMT

Data structure:

  • Multiple trade transactions will make up a complete position.
  • Positions will be defined by manually assigning a position number when a trade is entered. All trades with the same position number will be grouped together to form the position and profit/loss for that position will be calculated
  • Each position will be for a single underlying security
  • The first trade transaction entered for a trade number effectively opens that position.
  • Positions must be manually closed

Features:

  • The interface should be a single page with summary information at the top and individual positions below.
  • The summary information should include:
    • Number of active positions
    • Total trades in both active and closed positions
    • The running P&L for all open positions
    • The net P&L for all closed positions
  • For positions, there will be a toggle to limit the displayed positions to be either open positions or closed positions
  • Below the toggle - each position should be displayed in a tile that has summary information at the top but can be expanded for detail information
  • The position summary information will include:
    • The position number
    • The underlying security
    • The type of trade structure. Trade structures include:
      • Single
      • Vertical
      • Ratio
      • Butterfly
    • The running P&L for the position
    • The days to expiration for the position
    • The number of additional trades (adjustments) after the initial position trade was opened
  • Clicking on a position summary will expand the position to show all trades that make up the position.

Platform: This should be a chrome web app. Chrome may be running in MacOS, Windows, or even in iOS. The data could be stored in a google sheet or in an excel spreadsheet that is stored in the file system - likely dropbox to ensure access across my multiple computers.

Implemented Features

Core Functionality

Trade Parsing - Parses Thinkorswim trade format automatically - Supports spread types: SINGLE, VERTICAL (VERT), CALENDAR, DIAGONAL, BUTTERFLY (BFLY), RATIO, BACKRATIO, CUSTOM, ROLL variants - Handles BUY/SELL actions with correct sign conventions - Parses weekly vs standard options - Extracts strikes, expirations, option types (CALL/PUT) - Supports GTC orders and various order types (LMT, MKT)

Position Management - Manual position assignment when entering trades - Automatic position creation on first trade - Position close/reopen functionality - Position deletion - Trade deletion within positions - Open/Closed position filtering

Services (Portfolios) - Multiple services/portfolios support - Each service has its own set of positions - Service creation, renaming, deletion - Service-level P&L aggregation

P&L Calculations

Cost Basis Calculation - BUY trades: negative cost (money out) - SELL trades: positive cost (money in/credit received) - Handles multiplier (typically 100 for options)

Current P&L Logic (for open positions) - Net credit portfolios (Cost >= 0): P&L = Value only (credits are banked) - Net debit portfolios (Cost < 0): P&L = Cost + Value - This logic applies at the portfolio level, not individual position level

Closed P&L - Calculated as sum of all trade costs for closed positions - Filterable by time period (All Time, YTD, 90 days, 30 days, 7 days)

Mark-to-Market

Position Marking - Manual mark value entry per position - Mark date tracking - Mark source tracking (manual vs API) - Mark values cleared when position is closed

Display - Shows current mark value - Shows mark date - Calculates unrealized P&L based on marks

Tax Tracking

Taxable Flag - Each position has isTaxable boolean flag - Default: false (non-taxable) - Toggle in position card UI - Persists to Google Sheets

Tax Breakdown Display - Closed P&L split by taxable vs non-taxable - Current P&L split by taxable vs non-taxable - Shown on main summary page

UI Features

Main Page - Summary statistics at top - Service cards with key metrics - Collapsible Closed P&L chart (bar chart by period) - Service cards show expired position indicator (red tint)

Service View - Open/Closed position toggle - Position cards with expandable details - Days to Expiration (DTE) for open positions - Days Held for closed positions - Expired positions highlighted with red tint

Position Cards - Symbol, structure type, P&L - Trade count and adjustment count - Expandable trade details - Mark-to-market input - Taxable toggle checkbox - Close/Reopen/Delete actions - Edit position dates

Trade Entry - Text input for Thinkorswim format - Position number assignment (existing or new) - Parse preview before save - Delete individual trades

Trade String History - Automatically saves successful trade strings when added - History button shows all past trade strings for the service - Entries sorted most recent to oldest - Copy button for each entry to clipboard - Help button (?) explains how to copy from Thinkorswim

Trade Entry Help - Visual guide showing where to find trade strings in Thinkorswim - Screenshots of Activity & Positions and thinkLog Note dialog - Step-by-step instructions for copying trade data

Data Persistence

Local Storage - Automatic save to browser localStorage - Rehydrates dates on load - Supports legacy data migration (markPrice -> markValue)

Google Sheets Sync - OAuth authentication with Google - Automatic spreadsheet creation - 6 sheets: Metadata, Services, Positions, Trades, Legs, TradeHistory - Full sync (read/write all data) - Schema versioning

Spreadsheet Schema - Metadata: appTitle, schemaVersion, lastModified - Services: id, name, createdAt, nextPositionId - Positions: id, serviceId, symbol, structure, isOpen, openDate, closeDate, markValue, markDate, markSource, isTaxable - Trades: id, positionId, serviceId, rawInput, action, totalQuantity, symbol, multiplier, isWeekly, spreadType, price, orderType, isGTC, tradeDate - Legs: tradeId, legIndex, quantity, expiration, strike, optionType, legAction - TradeHistory: id, serviceId, tradeString, enteredDate, positionId

Deployment

Vercel Hosting - Static site deployment - Auto-deploy from GitHub - Production URL: https://options-tracker-phi.vercel.app

Google OAuth Configuration - Requires VITE_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID environment variable - Authorized origins and redirect URIs configured - Currently in testing mode (manual user approval required)

Technology Stack

  • Frontend: React 19 with TypeScript
  • Build Tool: Vite 7
  • Styling: Tailwind CSS 4
  • Charts: Chart.js with react-chartjs-2
  • APIs: Google Sheets API, Google Drive API
  • Hosting: Vercel
  • Version Control: Git/GitHub
